HB351 INTRODUCED
29 A BILL
30 TO BE ENTITLED
31 AN ACT
32
33 Relating to data privacy; to authorize a consumer to
34 take certain actions regarding the consumer's personal data;
35 to regulate the manner in which a controller may process
36 personal data; to provide for the obligations of a data
37 processor; to regulate the processing of deidentified data;
38 and to provide for enforcement of this act.
39 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF ALABAMA:
40 Section 1. This act shall be known as the Alabama
41 Personal Data Protection Act.
42 Section 2. For the purposes of this act, the following
43 terms have the following meanings:
44 (1) AFFILIATE. A legal entity that shares common
45 branding with another legal entity or that controls, is
46 controlled by, or is under common control with another legal
47 entity.
48 (2) ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE MODEL. The underlying
49 machine learning algorithm, along with its derived parameters,
50 including, but not limited to, weights, biases, and other
51 internal representations that result solely from the training
52 process, and which does not inherently contain personally
53 identifiable information unless that information has been
54 explicitly embedded in the algorithm. The term does not
55 include any downstream system or application that uses the
56 model.
Page 2

model.
HB351 INTRODUCED
57 (3) AUTHENTICATE. To use reasonable methods to
58 determine that a request to exercise any of the consumer
59 rights afforded under this act is being made by, or on behalf
60 of, a consumer who is entitled to exercise those consumer
61 rights with respect to the consumer's personal data at issue.
62 (4) BIOMETRIC DATA. Data generated by automatic
63 measurements of an individual's biological characteristics
64 such as a fingerprint, voiceprint, retina, or iris that are
65 used to identify a specific individual. The term does not
66 include any of the following:
67 a. A digital or physical photograph.
68 b. An audio or video recording.
69 c. Any data generated from paragraph a. or b. unless
70 the data is used to identify a specific individual.
71 (5) CHILD. An individual under 13 years of age.
72 (6) CONSENT. A clear affirmative act signifying a
73 consumer's freely given, specific, informed, and unambiguous
74 agreement to allow the processing of personal data relating to
75 the consumer, including, but not limited to, a written
76 statement or a statement by electronic means. The term does
77 not include any of the following:
78 a. Acceptance of a general or broad term of use or
79 similar document that contains descriptions of personal data
80 processing along with other unrelated information.
81 b. Hovering over, muting, or pausing a given piece of
82 content.
83 c. An agreement obtained using dark patterns.
84 (7) CONSUMER. An individual who is a resident of this
